Also, if you get a burn, put a slice ov potato on it and the starch draws the heat out of it to help mellow the pain. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udaveonsilverstring.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daveon Silverstring</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 66<br> <font color=#CC9900>(6/8/01 11:15:22 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.com/mcheeks/everquest/daveon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bards in large scale raids.</span><hr size=1> I think what Kestri (and others) are getting at (but are too polite to say) is that a good bard should already know what he or she should be playing by the time they hit raiding level.  You've been choosing and using your songs for 46+ levels (unless you PL'ed or soloed the whole way), you know best what songs you should be using for a given situation.<br>
<br>
Sure, you can just sit back and play manasong all raid if you're in an all caster group, or if you are someone who is coordinating the raid or distributing loot.  But just playing mana is really a waste of some of your abilities.<br>
<br>
If you're in a melee group, you should be doing your melee buff thing, but you can also use 3 Chants, or some combination of things (for instance, sometimes you don't have to haste your group because there's an enchanter designated to give haste to people on the raid).  Shield of Song with a lute is also a good way to prevent damage to your group if you have multiple people taking damage.<br>
<br>
Also, I will remind all bards that when fighting casters, that the mez songs will interrupt them.  Last night in Hate, I twice inturrupted Clerics of Innoruk from complete healing themselves by using Pixie Strike (I'm still 51st, so I don't have the upgrade yet).  You'll get a lot of resists in the planes with Pixie Strike, but sometimes those ones that do take hold are important.<br>
<br>
And generally, raids have two or more enchanters, so you usually don't have to mez at all on a raid.  But there are a couple times when you can help out with mez.  In Fear, if you are in the pull group, you can mez the pets of creatures, while the enchanter concentrates on the creatures themselves.  Since the pets are lower level, you should succeed most or all of the time, and even if mez breaks on them, they won't do a whole lot of damage to you before you mez them again (and better that they attack you than the enchanter).  In Hate, if there's a bad pull or strange aggro, you can mez if the enchanters have gone down.  Generally by that point, the raid may be facing wipe out, and you may be the only one left that has a chance to occupy the extras.<br>
<br>
We bards are very flexible in what we can do, and once you show your group how you can contribute, you'll never hear them say &quot;just play mana&quot;.<br>
<br>
 <p><b>--Daveon Silverstring<br>
--Nocturne Mist</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukestrithebard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KestriTheBard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=#FFFF66>Board Moderator  <br><font color=#A0B0E0>&lt;Clan Spiritslammer&gt;  </font></span><br>  Posts: 642<br> <font color=#CC9900>(6/8/01 1:11:42 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bards in large scale raids.</span><hr size=1> Heh I remember being on a raid in Hate and having mez memmed for some reason.  All of a sudden shots begin that the chanters are all dying, and there is only one left.  <br>
